Strict, machine-parsed source for the Plover JS/TS steno dictionary Б─■ the file `src/parse.ts` compiles into the actual Plover dictionary JSON. This is data, not code, but its syntax is a small custom template language and the file is the single source of truth for it; editing an entry here has zero effect until parse.ts runs.

**Entry shape**: a fenced block opens with a stroke (e.g. ` ````STKWR-F `), the fence body is the emitted template, and the closing fence is followed by zero or more directive lines (`@count`, `@arity`, `@multiline`, `@fuse`, `@type`, `@noarg`, `@literal`) that attach to the entry immediately above Б─■ not the next one. `###Name` immediately preceding an entry is a human label, ignored by the parser but useful for grep. `#`/`//` are line comments anywhere.

**Template operators** (only meaningful inside non-`@literal` blocks): `%0`-`%9` are tabstop/landing points (plain profile lands on `%0`; snippet expansions use the rest in order). `%d` emits the in-scope count as a literal digit Б─■ outside a `%[ %]` repeat it's the *total* count, inside one it's the *iteration index*; this dual meaning is the easiest thing to get backwards when adding a new templated entry. `%t` is a type-slot filled later by appending a type stroke (see below). `%b` is the body-break flag Б─■ toggles on/off across an entire translation, used to control one-line vs. block body forms. `%p` is a pattern-slot. `%[ sep | body %]` repeats `body` per count with `sep` joined between iterations (never after the last). `%(EXPR)` computes a landing-point index as a linear function of `d` (the loop index) instead of using a literal digit Б─■ the parser does not renumber conflicting landings, so overlapping `%(EXPR)` results are a hard error, not a silent merge. Escapes: `\n \t \{ \} \% \| \\ \``.

**Directives**: `@count KEYS` (e.g. `@count AOE`) declares which steno keys act as a bank selecting the repeat count for that entry's `%[ %]`/`%d`; drop or change this and the count logic breaks silently. `@arity N` marks a `@type` entry as needing N appended type-args before it's a complete/terminal type (e.g. `Map`, `Promise`, `Set`, `Record`, `Array`, `Generator` all have arity Б┴╔1 and stay non-terminal Б─■ i.e. still combinable with `/` selectors Б─■ until satisfied). `@type` marks a stroke as a *secondary* stroke appendable to fill a `%t` type-slot elsewhere; such entries are invalid as standalone translations. `@noarg` marks a `@type` entry as inherently arity-0/complete (e.g. `null`, `undefined`, `function`) even though it takes no generic. `@fuse` (used on the function family) means the appended return-type stroke merges into the *same* shape stroke rather than requiring an intermediate typeless stroke Б─■ `func-shape / TPH-FLT` produces a fully-typed function directly. `@multiline` marks an entry (the two `switch` variants) as always spanning multiple physical lines regardless of `%b` state. `@literal` (used only in the data-structures section) means the fence body is emitted verbatim with no `%`-operator processing at all Б─■ these are complete, multi-line TS class definitions (linked list, stack, queue, deque, both heaps, binary tree, BST, graph, trie), so `%`, `{`, `}` inside them are plain characters, not template syntax.

**Structural families to know about when adding entries**: the array/string/math "method chain" family keys off a shared prefix stroke (`STKWR*PLT`) plus a `/`-suffixed selector stroke per method Б─■ the prefix alone is `pre-method` (non-emitting placeholder), so a new method needs both the selector stroke *and* to be listed under the right sub-root (array vs `STR-` vs `PH-`). The type system (`TPH`=number, `STR`=string, `PW`=boolean, `PR`=Promise, `PH`=Map, `KR`=Record, `ST`=Set, `R`=Array, `SKWR`=Generator, etc.) is consumed by any `%t` slot anywhere in the file and by the standalone type-emitter stroke `STKWR-T` (append any type stroke after it to emit that type free-standing, e.g. for casts/assertions Б─■ `STKWR-T/TPH` Б├▓ `number`). Changing a type stroke's arity or removing `@noarg` changes parsing behavior for every function/param/declaration entry that uses `%t`, not just the type section.

No other file's format is defined here, but everything downstream (`src